{"timestamp": "2026-03-17T01:24:54.830199", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Valine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Valine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of valine: routes, evidence, and unresolved challenges\n\n**The Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, HCN, and ammonia remains the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to valine**, yet the availability of the branched-chain aldehyde precursor constitutes the central bottleneck in the entire pathway. Valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid, C\u2085H\u2081\u2081NO\u2082) has been confirmed in reanalyzed Miller-Urey spark discharge samples, detected at **~300\u20131,000 ppb in the Murchison meteorite** as a racemic mixture, and shown to be thermodynamically favorable for synthesis under moderate hydrothermal conditions. Despite this convergent evidence for abiotic formation, prebiotic valine production yields remain far below those of simpler amino acids like glycine, and the selective prebiotic generation of its branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor from simple feedstocks (H\u2082O, CO\u2082, NH\u2083, HCN, CH\u2084) has never been cleanly demonstrated. This report synthesizes the full landscape of known synthesis routes, experimental evidence, environmental constraints, catalytic requirements, and open problems relevant to incorporating valine into prebiotic synthesis network models.\n\n---\n\n## Seven distinct routes connect simple molecules to valine\n\nThe literature documents multiple pathways from prebiotic feedstocks to valine, though they vary enormously in experimental support and plausibility. The dominant and best-characterized route is the **Strecker synthesis**, while several alternative pathways offer complementary or supporting roles.\n\n**Strecker synthesis.** The most established pathway proceeds in three steps. First, isobutyraldehyde ((CH\u2083)\u2082CHCHO) reacts with ammonia to form an imine (Schiff base). Second, HCN adds nucleophilically to the imine, producing 2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile (the \u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate). Third, hydrolysis of the nitrile group through an amide intermediate yields racemic DL-valine. The reaction proceeds optimally in aqueous solution at **pH ~9** (where free NH\u2083 is available, pK\u2090 = 9.2) and mild temperatures. The equilibration steps are reversible, but hydrolysis is irreversible, driving the reaction forward. Miller and Van Trump (1981, *Origin of Life*) established this as the operative mechanism in spark discharge experiments, and Keefe, Newton, and Miller (1995, *Nature*) confirmed isobutyraldehyde as the specific Strecker aldehyde precursor for valine. Devergne, Magrino, Pietrucci, and Saitta (2021, *Journal of Physical Chemistry Letters*) computed the full free-energy landscape of the Strecker mechanism from first principles, confirming its thermodynamic feasibility. A variant pathway, the **Bucherer-Bergs reaction**, proceeds through hydantoin intermediates when CO\u2082 is present alongside HCN and NH\u2083, bridging aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry with \u03b1-keto acid metabolism (Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy, 2022, *Nature Chemistry*).\n\n**Miller-Urey spark discharge.** Electric discharges through reducing gas mixtures (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082, H\u2082O) generate HCN and various aldehydes in the gas phase, which dissolve and undergo Strecker chemistry in the aqueous reservoir. While Miller's original 1953 paper (*Science*) reported only five amino acids using crude paper chromatography, modern reanalyses by Bada's group confirmed valine among **22 amino acids** in the volcanic apparatus samples (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*) and **23 amino acids** in the H\u2082S-enriched experiment (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*). Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS*) had earlier confirmed all coded \u03b1-amino acids including valine using improved gas compositions.\n\n**Reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.** The keto acid pathway \u2014 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH\u2083 + 2[H] \u2192 valine + H\u2082O \u2014 parallels biological valine biosynthesis. Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, and Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Letters*) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids using FeS/H\u2082S as the reducing system coupled with pyrite formation. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, *Tetrahedron Letters*) revisited the reaction with freshly precipitated FeS or Fe(OH)\u2082. Most recently, Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) achieved reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine on mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide minerals at alkaline pH, and Kaur, Rauscher, Werner, and colleagues (2024, *Chem*) drove the reductive amination of six biological keto acids using H\u2082 on metallic nickel catalyst at 22\u00b0C and pH 8. Although \u03b1-ketoisovalerate specifically was not always the test substrate, the chemistry extends in principle to the valine precursor.\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry.** Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland (2015, *Nature Chemistry*) demonstrated a unified protometabolic network producing precursors to RNA, proteins, and lipids from HCN, H\u2082S, and phosphate under UV irradiation with Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling. The system generates Strecker aminonitrile precursors for **six proteinogenic amino acids**, but the reductive homologation chemistry primarily builds C\u2081\u2013C\u2083 aldehydes. **Valine's branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor is not directly produced** in published cyanosulfidic schemes, though Sutherland's \"flow chemistry\" model envisions geochemical streams where aldol condensation could extend the carbon chain.\n\n**Fischer-Tropsch type (FTT) synthesis** at hydrothermal vents \u2014 CO + H\u2082 on Fe/Ni catalysts at 150\u2013300\u00b0C \u2014 primarily generates hydrocarbons, fatty acids, and alcohols (McCollom, Ritter, and Simoneit, 1999, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*). FTT reactions are more relevant to generating aldehyde precursors that could then feed Strecker chemistry than to directly producing amino acids. **HCN oligomerization** yields predominantly glycine and alanine upon hydrolysis (Ferris, Joshi, Edelson, and Lawless, 1978, *Journal of Molecular Evolution*); valine is not a significant product because the polymer structure favors linear, small amino acids. **Formose-type chemistry** from formaldehyde produces hydroxylated sugars and branched ketoses but not the non-hydroxylated branched aldehydes required for valine synthesis, though side reactions under basic conditions generate complex aldehyde mixtures that could include trace isobutyraldehyde.\n\n---\n\n## The isobutyraldehyde bottleneck and other critical intermediates\n\nThe central challenge in prebiotic valine synthesis is not the Strecker reaction itself \u2014 which proceeds readily when all reactants are present \u2014 but rather the upstream generation of the branched C\u2084 aldehyde precursor isobutyraldehyde from simpler molecules. This bottleneck distinguishes valine from simpler amino acids like glycine (from formaldehyde) and alanine (from acetaldehyde), whose aldehyde precursors are far more abundant in prebiotic scenarios.\n\n**Isobutyraldehyde formation** has been proposed through several routes, none fully satisfactory. Aldol condensation of acetaldehyde \u2014 itself readily formed from ethanol oxidation or spark discharge chemistry \u2014 can produce branched C\u2083\u2013C\u2084 species, but selectivity for isobutyraldehyde is poor. Preiner et al. (2023, *Nature Communications*) demonstrated that NiS-catalyzed acetylene chemistry produces acetaldehyde which undergoes aldol diversification to higher aldehydes including branched species. In spark discharge experiments, radical recombination processes (CH\u2083\u2022 combining with CHO-containing fragments) generate branched aldehydes among a complex product mixture, explaining how valine appears in Miller-Urey experiments. Decarboxylation of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate provides another route but simply shifts the precursor problem one step back. The statistical and kinetic disfavoring of branching over linear chain extension in abiotic aldol chemistry means that **isobutyraldehyde concentrations would have been orders of magnitude lower** than those of formaldehyde and acetaldehyde under any plausible prebiotic scenario.\n\n**\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate (3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid)** serves as an alternative entry point to valine through reductive amination, bypassing the Strecker pathway entirely. Its prebiotic formation could proceed through condensation reactions of pyruvate with acetaldehyde, paralleling the biological acetolactate synthase pathway, or through non-enzymatic Krebs cycle analogs (Muchowska, Varma, and Moran, 2019, *Nature*). Copley, Smith, and Morowitz (2005, *PNAS*) proposed that dinucleotide cofactors could catalyze amino acid formation from \u03b1-keto acids. Krishnamurthy's group recently demonstrated abiotic generation of \u03b1-keto acids from amino acids via phosphorylation and \u03b2-elimination, coupled with transamination (2025, *PMC*). These pathways are metabolically congruent \u2014 they mirror modern biosynthetic logic \u2014 but prebiotic availability of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate itself remains experimentally undemonstrated.\n\nThe **\u03b1-aminonitrile intermediate** (2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile) is well-characterized. Miller (1998) estimated half-lives for aminonitrile hydrolysis at **less than 1,000 years at 0\u00b0C**, accelerating dramatically at higher temperatures. Green, Xu, and Sutherland (2021, 2023, *JACS*) showed that N-formylation of aminonitriles in formamide solvent protects them from reversion of the Strecker equilibrium, potentially improving amino acid yields.\n\nHCN and ammonia, the two other essential Strecker reactants, face their own availability constraints. Miyakawa et al. (2002) estimated steady-state oceanic HCN at **2 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2076 M at pH 8 and 0\u00b0C**, dropping to **7 \u00d7 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 M at 100\u00b0C** due to hydrolysis. Ammonia concentrations in prebiotic oceans are estimated at **10\u207b\u2075 to 10\u207b\u00b3 M**. Both reagents compete across multiple reaction pathways, further limiting flux through the valine-specific Strecker channel.\n\n---\n\n## Alkaline vents and evaporitic pools offer the most plausible settings\n\nThe environmental context for prebiotic valine synthesis is constrained by a fundamental tension: higher temperatures accelerate both synthesis and decomposition, creating a narrow productive window. Two environments emerge as most favorable, each suited to different steps in the pathway.\n\n**Alkaline hydrothermal vents (Lost City type)** provide the strongest thermodynamic case. Operating at **40\u201390\u00b0C and pH 9\u201311**, these systems generate abundant H\u2082 through serpentinization of olivine, creating reducing conditions that thermodynamically favor organic synthesis. Amend and Shock (1998, *Science*) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of all 20 proteinogenic amino acids, including valine, is **exergonic under hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal conditions** but endergonic in cold surface seawater. Martin and Russell (2007, *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*) proposed that pH and redox gradients at the vent-ocean interface could drive a primitive acetyl-CoA pathway with reductive amination as the amino acid synthesis step. Microporous chimney structures provide natural compartmentalization that concentrates reactants. Iron oxyhydroxide minerals, Fe(II)-bearing sulfides, and saponite clays present at these vents serve as catalysts. M\u00e9nez et al. (2018, *Nature*) documented abiotic formation of tryptophan in serpentinites beneath the Atlantis Massif, catalyzed by iron-rich saponite clay \u2014 the first field evidence for abiotic amino acid synthesis in a hydrothermal system.\n\n**Black smoker vents (>300\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133)** are far less favorable. Miller and Bada (1988, *Nature*) demonstrated that amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C**, with decomposition rates vastly exceeding synthesis rates at black smoker temperatures. However, rapid cold-quenching effects in flow reactors can preserve amino acid aggregates even after brief (**2-minute**) exposure at 200\u2013250\u00b0C (Chandru, Imai, Kaneko, Obayashi, and Kobayashi, 2013, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*), suggesting that transit through high-temperature zones followed by rapid cooling could preserve products.\n\n**Surface evaporitic pools and warm little ponds** complement vent synthesis by providing concentration and polymerization. Wet-dry cycling drives condensation reactions that produce peptide bonds \u2014 Forsythe et al. (2015, *Angewandte Chemie*) demonstrated ester-mediated amide bond formation through this mechanism. Campbell et al. (2019, *Nature Communications*) showed that deliquescent minerals (K\u207a/Na\u207a salts) mediate glycine oligomerization during wet-dry cycles at 100\u2013120\u00b0C, yielding oligomers **over 10-fold higher than controls**. UV radiation in the absence of an ozone layer is a double-edged factor: it drives photochemistry producing HCN and aldehydes but also degrades amino acids. Urea-containing pools can produce carbamoyl amino acids with ~100% yield under UV, providing protective derivatization (2023, *Earth and Planetary Science Letters*).\n\nThe **optimal temperature window for prebiotic valine synthesis** is likely **50\u2013150\u00b0C**, balancing synthesis rate against decomposition. Hydrophobic amino acids including valine are generally more thermally stable than hydrophilic ones like serine and aspartic acid (Sato et al., 2004). Li and Brill (2003) measured valine decarboxylation rates at 310\u2013330\u00b0C comparable to those of leucine and isoleucine, while Pietrucci and Aponte et al. (2018, *ACS Earth and Space Chemistry*) computed decomposition rates of **10\u207b\u00b9\u00b9 to 10\u207b\u00b9\u00b3 s\u207b\u00b9 at 100\u00b0C**, corresponding to half-lives of **~1,000 to tens of thousands of years**.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts bridge thermodynamic gaps and concentrate products\n\nThree classes of minerals play distinct roles in prebiotic valine chemistry: iron-sulfur phases drive redox reactions, clay minerals concentrate and polymerize products, and semiconductor minerals enable photocatalysis.\n\n**Iron-sulfur minerals** form the catalytic backbone of W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world hypothesis. Pyrite formation (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + 2H\u207a + 2e\u207b) provides reducing equivalents for organic synthesis. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (*Science*, 1997; 1998; 2003) demonstrated activated acetic acid synthesis from CO + CH\u2083SH on (Fe,Ni)S, peptide formation from amino acids activated with CO on (Ni,Fe)S at 100\u00b0C, and reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids with freshly precipitated FeS. A 2024 study in *Nature Communications* revealed that natural pyrite surfaces exhibit **photocatalytic reductive amination** of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids with D-enantiomeric excesses of **14.5\u201342.4%**, driven by the wavy atomic arrangement of the pyrite surface. Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084), structurally analogous to biological [Fe\u2084S\u2084] ferredoxin clusters (Russell et al., 1994), and mackinawite (FeS) serve as additional catalytic phases. Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS*) showed that the **Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio** in mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxides is a critical parameter determining whether reductive amination (producing amino acids) or reduction (producing hydroxy acids) dominates.\n\n**Clay minerals**, particularly montmorillonite, serve primarily as concentration and polymerization agents. Montmorillonite-catalyzed oligomerization of activated monomers proceeds **100\u20131,000 times faster** than hydrolysis (Kawamura and Ferris, 1994), and Ferris et al. (1996, *Nature*) produced oligomers up to **55 monomers** on mineral surfaces. For amino acids specifically, cation exchange is the dominant adsorption mechanism, with cationic amino acids (arginine, lysine) adsorbed with Langmuir constants **30\u201350\u00d7 greater** than zwitterionic species like valine (Millman et al., 2024, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*). Iron-rich saponite clay catalyzes Friedel-Crafts reactions that produce aromatic amino acids in serpentinites (M\u00e9nez et al., 2018, *Nature*). Layered double hydroxides facilitate prebiotic peptide formation with a ribosome-like catalytic mechanism, where hydrophobic amino acids including valine aggregate within clay layers enabling peptide hydrophobic collapse (*Nature Communications*, 2017).\n\n**Semiconductor minerals** enable photocatalytic pathways. ZnS drives reversible amination of \u03b1-oxo acids to amino acids on photo-illuminated surfaces (Wang et al., 2012, *Origins of Life and Evolution of Biospheres*) and catalyzes three of five steps in the reverse TCA cycle, achieving **95% yield** for fumarate-to-succinate conversion (Guzman and Martin, 2016). Chiral mesostructured ZnS can drive enantioselective amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082 reduction (2024, *ScienceDirect*). TiO\u2082, the most active photocatalytic semiconductor in Earth's crust (0.01\u20131 wt%), catalyzes C\u2013C bond formation and conversion of formamide to nucleobases (Saladino et al., 2006, *PNAS*), with negligible temperature dependence allowing product accumulation without thermal decomposition.\n\n---\n\n## From Miller's spark flask to Murchison: converging experimental evidence\n\nLaboratory experiments and meteoritic analyses provide complementary lines of evidence for abiotic valine formation, though quantitative yields remain modest.\n\n**Miller-Urey experiments** tell a story of improving analytical sensitivity revealing increasing molecular diversity. Miller's 1953 classic experiment identified only five amino acids. When Bada's group reanalyzed Miller's archived samples using HPLC-FD and LC-ToF-MS, the volcanic apparatus yielded **22 amino acids including valine** (Johnson et al., 2008, *Science*), and the 1958 H\u2082S experiment produced **23 amino acids** with dramatically enhanced alkyl amino acid yields (Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*). The H\u2082S samples showed amino acid yields **several hundred times larger** than the original and volcanic experiments for some species. All amino acids were racemic, confirming abiotic origin. Glycine yields reach ~2.1% of input carbon in the classic apparatus; valine yields are roughly **~0.04\u20130.05% of carbon**, approximately 5% the yield of glycine.\n\n**Proton and photon irradiation experiments** expand the energy source repertoire. Kobayashi et al. (2023, *Life*) showed that **2.5 MeV proton irradiation** (simulating galactic cosmic rays) produces amino acids from CO\u2082 + CH\u2084 + N\u2082 + H\u2082O mixtures even at methane ratios as low as **0.5%**, whereas spark discharges require \u226515% methane and UV irradiation produces no amino acids even at 50% methane. Nuevo et al. (2008, *Monthly Notices of the Royal Astronomical Society*) detected 13 amino acids including valine from UV/EUV irradiation of naphthalene in H\u2082O + NH\u2083 ice at 15 K, demonstrating interstellar ice processing as a viable amino acid source.\n\n**Meteoritic detection** provides the strongest evidence for widespread abiotic amino acid synthesis. Kvenvolden et al. (1970, *Nature*) first identified valine in the Murchison meteorite as **nearly equal D and L enantiomers**. Cronin and Pizzarello (1983, *Advances in Space Research*) expanded the Murchison amino acid inventory to 52 species. Valine concentrations in Murchison range from **~300 to 1,000 ppb**, compared to glycine at 3,000\u20136,000 ppb and \u03b1-aminoisobutyric acid (a non-protein amino acid) at even higher levels. Pizzarello and Cronin (2000, *Geochimica et Cosmochimica Acta*) confirmed that valine in meteorites is **essentially racemic** (D/L \u2248 1.0), in stark contrast to its structural analog isovaline, which shows L-enantiomeric excesses up to **18.5 \u00b1 2.4%** in Murchison (Glavin and Dworkin, 2009, *PNAS*). Valine has been confirmed in Murchison, Murray, Orgueil, and Aguas Zarcas meteorites, with amino acid abundance decreasing systematically with increasing carbon number and structural complexity \u2014 consistent with Strecker synthesis from a distribution of available aldehydes.\n\n**Extraterrestrial in situ detections** remain limited. Only glycine has been confirmed in cometary material \u2014 at comet Wild 2 by Stardust (Elsila et al., 2009) and at comet 67P by Rosetta/ROSINA (Altwegg et al., 2016, *Science Advances*). No amino acids, including valine, have been definitively detected on Mars; SAM on Curiosity found chlorinated organics but perchlorates complicate amino acid preservation and detection.\n\n---\n\n## Five fundamental challenges define the frontier\n\nDespite substantial progress, prebiotic valine synthesis faces five interconnected challenges that remain actively debated.\n\n**The branched-precursor problem** is paramount. No known efficient prebiotic pathway selectively generates isobutyraldehyde or \u03b1-ketoisovalerate from C\u2081 feedstocks. Formaldehyde and acetaldehyde \u2014 precursors to glycine and alanine \u2014 are among the most abundant products of atmospheric photochemistry, spark discharges, and interstellar chemistry. Isobutyraldehyde requires a specific branching event that is kinetically disfavored relative to linear chain extension. This thermodynamic and kinetic asymmetry explains why valine yields are consistently **5\u201310% those of glycine** across all experimental systems. The most promising avenues involve aldol diversification on NiS catalysts (Preiner et al., 2023), radical recombination in reducing atmospheres (Parker et al., 2011), or meteoritic/cometary delivery of complex aldehyde mixtures.\n\n**The homochirality problem** remains unsolved. All known abiotic synthesis routes produce racemic valine, yet biology uses exclusively L-valine. Proposed symmetry-breaking mechanisms include circularly polarized light producing >1.3% enantiomeric excess in ice analogs (de Marcellus et al., 2011), pyrite photocatalysis generating 14.5\u201342.4% D-amino acid excess (*Nature Communications*, 2024), and the CISS (Chiral-Induced Spin Selectivity) effect on magnetized magnetite surfaces (Ozturk et al., 2022, *PNAS*). A 2025 proposal (*PNAS*) suggests homochirality emerged network-wide through CISS-induced ee on magnetite, amplified by conglomerate crystallization of ribo-aminooxazoline to 100% ee, then propagated to amino acids. Notably, valine itself may not undergo efficient chiral selection on calcite crystal faces because its side chain provides insufficient configuration-dependent interaction points for the three-point binding rule (Hazen et al., 2001, *PNAS*).\n\n**The concentration problem** is severe for all amino acids but especially for lower-yield species like valine. Even optimistic prebiotic scenarios yield oceanic amino acid concentrations far below those needed for polymerization. Evaporative concentration in tidal pools, mineral surface adsorption, eutectic freezing in ice (where HCN polymerization proceeds efficiently at \u22122\u00b0C), and aerosol enrichment (10\u00b2\u201310\u2074 fold) have all been proposed. Black et al. (2019, *PNAS*) showed that transiently concentrated amino acids from drying bind to and stabilize fatty acid membranes, with stabilization persisting after redilution. Tectonic fault zone vesicles at ~1 km depth may selectively trap hydrophobic amino acids like valine (Mayer et al., 2017, *Life*).\n\n**Thermal decomposition** constrains all high-temperature scenarios. Valine decomposes via parallel decarboxylation (\u2192 isobutylamine + CO\u2082) and deamination (\u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH\u2083) pathways. At 100\u00b0C, half-lives are estimated at **~10\u00b3\u201310\u2074 years**; at 250\u00b0C, amino acids degrade to less than 1% within **25 hours** (Lemke et al., 2009). Miller and Bada's (1988) demonstration that amino acids are irreversibly destroyed at 240\u00b0C remains a foundational constraint on black smoker origin scenarios, though rapid transit with cold quenching could preserve products formed during brief high-temperature exposure.\n\n**Competition for shared reactants** limits valine's share of the product distribution. HCN, NH\u2083, and reducing equivalents are consumed by all Strecker pathways simultaneously; more abundant aldehyde precursors (formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, glycolaldehyde) outcompete isobutyraldehyde for these shared reagents. Side reactions including Cannizzaro disproportionation of isobutyraldehyde to isobutanol and isobutyric acid, and aldol condensation to higher products, further reduce the flux toward valine. The consistent amino acid distribution pattern \u2014 glycine >> alanine >> valine \u2014 observed across spark discharge experiments, meteorites, and theoretical models reflects these fundamental constraints.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion\n\nPrebiotic valine synthesis sits at a revealing intersection of established chemistry and persistent challenges. The Strecker pathway is mechanistically well-understood and experimentally confirmed across multiple independent systems \u2014 from Miller's spark flask to carbonaceous meteorites. Reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on iron-containing minerals offers a metabolically congruent alternative that connects prebiotic chemistry directly to extant biosynthetic logic. Alkaline hydrothermal vents provide the most thermodynamically favorable environment, while surface evaporitic pools offer the concentration and cycling dynamics needed for downstream polymerization.\n\nThe critical insight for prebiotic network design is that **valine's synthesis bottleneck is not the amino acid-forming reaction itself but the upstream generation of its branched C\u2084 precursor**. This contrasts sharply with glycine and alanine, where precursor availability is not limiting. Any realistic prebiotic synthesis network must therefore include explicit pathways for branched aldehyde or branched keto acid generation \u2014 likely through aldol diversification on transition metal sulfide catalysts, radical chemistry in reducing atmospheres, or meteoritic/cometary delivery. The consistent ~20-fold yield deficit of valine relative to glycine across all experimental systems quantifies the kinetic cost of molecular branching and should be incorporated as a constraint in network flux models. The racemic nature of meteoritic valine, the unresolved homochirality problem, and the narrow thermal stability window (50\u2013150\u00b0C optimal) further define the parameter space within which any viable prebiotic scenario must operate.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: This is a thoughtfully designed synthesis network that demonstrates strong alignment with the prebiotic valine literature. The network excels in several key areas: (1) **Topology** is excellent with 5 genuine hub molecules, 10 distinct pathways, and 5 convergence points providing good redundancy; (2) **Literature alignment** is outstanding \u2014 the Strecker, Bucherer-Bergs, and reductive amination routes are all well-cited in the research, and the identification of the branched-precursor bottleneck as the central challenge is explicitly captured; (3) **Environmental flow** generally follows the expected Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical progression; (4) **Multiple independent acetaldehyde sources** (FTT, NiS-acetylene, pyruvate decarboxylation) provide robustness. However, several issues prevent a higher score: (A) **rxn_006 is chemically incorrect as written** \u2014 simple aldol condensation of 2 acetaldehydes yields linear 3-hydroxybutanal, not branched isobutyraldehyde; the branched product requires either complex aldol diversification mixtures or radical recombination, and the stoichiometry should reflect this; (B) **NH3 and HCN are labeled as hub_intermediates but have no synthesis reactions** \u2014 they function as dangling inputs, reducing true network connectivity; (C) **rxn_007** (pyruvate + acetaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is experimentally undemonstrated and lacks a mineral catalyst specification; (D) **rxn_011 is stoichiometrically incomplete** \u2014 missing an explicit electron/hydrogen source for photocatalytic reductive amination; (E) **Some Surface reactions lack mineral agent specifications** as required by evaluation criteria. Despite these issues, the overall network strategy is sound, captures the essential prebiotic chemistry of valine, and correctly identifies the ~20-fold yield deficit relative to glycine as a consequence of the aldol branching bottleneck. The Bucherer-Bergs pathways (P9, P10) represent the strongest routes due to the thermodynamic driving force provided by hydantoin formation.\n- Issues: ['Clean Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical flow. The RWGS and FTT steps are well-supported. However, rxn_006 (2 acetaldehyde \u2192 isobutyraldehyde) is chemically problematic: simple aldol condensation of two acetaldehydes yields 3-hydroxybutanal (acetaldol) or crotonaldehyde, not the branched isobutyraldehyde. A complex mixture of aldol/retro-aldol products may include trace isobutyraldehyde, but the stoichiometry as written is misleading. Strecker and hydrolysis steps are textbook. No mineral catalyst specified for rxn_006.', 'Shorter pathway using NiS-catalyzed acetylene hydration (Preiner et al. 2023 aligned). Same rxn_006 isobutyraldehyde problem. Strecker and hydrolysis steps are robust. Overall a clean environmental flow with fewer steps.', 'Elegant use of pyruvate as both a metabolic intermediate and acetaldehyde source via decarboxylation. CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite is supported by Muchowska, Varma & Moran (2019). Same rxn_006 bottleneck. Slightly longer and less direct, but adds metabolic congruence.', 'Convergent pathway merging FTT-derived acetaldehyde with greigite-derived pyruvate. Reductive amination on FeS/H2S is well-supported (Hafenbradl 1995, Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 2003). However, rxn_007 (pyruvate + acetaldehyde \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) is experimentally undemonstrated for this specific product and lacks a specified mineral catalyst. Environmental flow goes Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Hydrothermal, which is somewhat unusual but could be justified by vent proximity to surface pools.', 'Shorter convergent variant using acetylene-derived acetaldehyde. Same rxn_007 weakness. Reductive amination step is strong. Environmental flow has the same H\u2192S\u2192H issue as P4.', \"Most metabolically congruent pathway \u2014 mirrors biological valine biosynthesis logic (pyruvate \u2192 keto acid \u2192 amino acid). Pyruvate serves dual role as both C3 keto acid and acetaldehyde source. The rxn_007 step remains the weak link. Strong alignment with W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's metabolic-first hypothesis.\", 'Photocatalytic reductive amination on pyrite is supported by 2024 Nature Communications data. However, rxn_011 as written is missing an explicit electron/hydrogen source \u2014 pyrite photocatalysis uses light + water as the electron donor. The rxn_007 step remains problematic. Environmental flow is better than P4-P6 since final step stays on surface.', 'Shorter variant of P7. Same issues with rxn_007 and rxn_011 stoichiometry.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid)\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network models valine synthesis through three major convergent strategies grounded in the literature: (1) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, HCN, and NH3 \u2014 the most experimentally validated route (Miller & Van Trump 1981; Keefe, Newton & Miller 1995); (2) Bucherer-Bergs variant through a hydantoin intermediate when CO2 is present (Pulletikurti et al. 2022); and (3) reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on iron-sulfur minerals, paralleling biological biosynthesis (Hafenbradl et al. 1995; Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 2003; 2024 Nature Communications pyrite photocatalysis). The central bottleneck \u2014 prebiotic generation of the branched C4 aldehyde isobutyraldehyde \u2014 is addressed via two routes: NiS-catalyzed aldol diversification of acetaldehyde (Preiner et al. 2023) producing branched species among a complex mixture, and direct Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis as a minor branched product on Fe-Ni catalysts (McCollom et al. 1999). Acetaldehyde itself is generated through three independent hydrothermal pathways (FTT, NiS-acetylene hydration, pyruvate decarboxylation), creating robust network redundancy. The metabolically congruent \u03b1-ketoisovalerate route proceeds via pyruvate-acetaldehyde condensation to acetolactate followed by decarboxylation, paralleling biological acetolactate synthase logic (Copley, Smith & Morowitz 2005). Four hub molecules (acetaldehyde, pyruvate, isobutyraldehyde, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) create the convergence topology. The ~20-fold yield deficit of valine vs. glycine observed across all experimental systems (Johnson et al. 2008; Parker et al. 2011; meteoritic data) is an intrinsic consequence of the kinetic and thermodynamic cost of C4 branching in aldol chemistry.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen gas\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon monoxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO/c1-2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"water\",\n      \"common_name\": \"water\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2S\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen sulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ethyne\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHO2-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvate / pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-methylpropanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"isobutyraldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H10N2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H10N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-(propan-2-yl)-imidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-isopropylhydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C6H10N2O2/c1-3(2)4-5(9)8-6(10)7-4/h3-4H,1-2H3,(H2,7,8,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"acetolactate (2-acetolactic acid)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)4(2,9)5(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H11NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"valine (DL-valine)\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO2 binds to Fe-S cluster surface of greigite (structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters). H2 dissociates on mineral surface providing reducing equivalents. Two-electron reduction of CO2 to formate (HCOO-) proceeds via a surface-bound formate intermediate. This is the first step in the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway analog.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is thermodynamically favorable under alkaline hydrothermal conditions (Amend & Shock, 1998, Science). Russell et al. (1994) proposed greigite as a structural and functional analog of biological ferredoxin [Fe4S4] clusters. Martin & Russell (2007, Philos. Trans. R. Soc. B) elaborated this as the basis of a primitive acetyl-CoA pathway. Formate serves as a C1 building block for downstream synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"awaruite (Ni3Fe)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-500 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite (Fe3O4) and Fe-Ni alloy\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Black smoker/high-temperature vent with rapid quenching to preserve products\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"CO adsorbs on Fe-Ni catalyst surface, dissociates to surface carbide and oxide. Sequential hydrogenation builds C1 to C2 chain (surface CH2 + CHO coupling). Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) is released as a C2 oxygenated product alongside methanol, ethanol, and higher homologs. Product preservation requires rapid cooling as amino acids degrade above 240\u00b0C (Miller & Bada, 1988).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom, Ritter & Simoneit (1999, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated FTT synthesis of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes from CO + H2 on Fe catalysts at 150-300\u00b0C. Acetaldehyde is a common C2 oxygenated product. Rapid quenching upon mixing with cold seawater preserves products (Chandru et al., 2013, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.). This is the primary hydrothermal route to the C2 aldehyde required for aldol chain extension.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"NiS-catalyzed acetylene hydration to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"nickel sulfide (NiS)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate (10-100 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"freshly precipitated NiS\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal conditions, pH 8-10\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetylene coordinates to Ni(II) centers on the NiS surface. Nucleophilic addition of water across the triple bond, facilitated by the metal center, produces vinyl alcohol which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde (Markovnikov addition). NiS acts as a heterogeneous catalyst recycled on the mineral surface.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2023, Nature Communications) demonstrated that NiS catalyzes acetylene chemistry to produce acetaldehyde, which then undergoes aldol diversification to higher aldehydes including branched species. This provides a direct hydrothermal route to the C2 building block. Acetylene is produced by high-temperature volcanic chemistry and serpentinization processes.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (50-200 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/magnetite mixed phases\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, strongly reducing (H2-rich)\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multi-step CO2 fixation on Fe-S mineral surfaces. CO2 is first reduced to formate, then to formaldehyde/CO equivalents, which undergo C-C coupling on the mineral surface to build the C3 backbone. The \u03b1-keto acid functional group arises from partial oxidation during the assembly. Pyruvate is thermodynamically the most stable C3 keto acid under these conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Muchowska, Varma & Moran (2019, Nature) demonstrated non-enzymatic Krebs cycle analogs including pyruvate formation from simple precursors on iron-containing minerals. Amend & Shock (1998, Science) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of organic molecules including amino acid precursors is exergonic under hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal conditions. Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub in both modern and plausibly prebiotic metabolism.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pyrite surface (facilitates decarboxylation)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Thermal decarboxylation favored at higher temperatures in hydrothermal fluids\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Non-oxidative decarboxylation of pyruvate: CH3COCOO- \u2192 CH3CHO + CO2. The \u03b2-keto acid undergoes facile loss of CO2 from the carboxylate group. Mineral surfaces (pyrite, magnetite) lower the activation energy by stabilizing the transition state through surface coordination of the carboxylate. This is the reverse of the carboxylation that forms pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate is a well-established reaction; pyruvate decarboxylation occurs readily at temperatures above 70\u00b0C and is accelerated by mineral surfaces. This provides a third independent route to acetaldehyde. The reaction parallels biological pyruvate decarboxylase activity and connects the C3 keto acid pool to the C2 aldehyde pool essential for valine precursor synthesis.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"NiS-catalyzed aldol diversification of acetaldehyde to branched aldehydes\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"nickel sulfide (NiS)\", \"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"NiS particles on montmorillonite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Mildly alkaline evaporitic pool (pH 8-10). Reaction produces a complex mixture of linear and branched C3-C6 aldehydes; isobutyraldehyde is a minor but thermodynamically accessible branched C4 product. Yield of isobutyraldehyde estimated at ~1-5% of total aldol products.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acetaldehyde undergoes repeated aldol condensation and retro-aldol scrambling on NiS surfaces. The initial aldol of two acetaldehydes yields 3-hydroxybutanal (acetaldol, linear C4), which can dehydrate to crotonaldehyde or undergo retro-aldol to regenerate C2 fragments. Under continued cycling, cross-aldol reactions and retro-aldol/re-aldol scrambling produce a statistical distribution of C3-C6 aldehydes including both linear (butanal, pentanal) and branched species (isobutyraldehyde, 2-methylbutanal). The branched isobutyraldehyde is formed when a C1 formyl fragment from retro-aldol adds to propionaldehyde, or through methylation-equivalent rearrangements on the NiS surface. NiS catalysis lowers activation barriers for both forward aldol and retro-aldol, enabling thermodynamic equilibration that populates branched isomers.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Preiner et al. (2023, Nature Communications) demonstrated NiS-catalyzed acetaldehyde diversification to higher aldehydes including branched species. This is NOT a simple stoichiometric aldol of 2 acetaldehydes to isobutyraldehyde; rather, it is a complex catalytic scrambling process. The branched C4 aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde) is a minor product (~1-5%) in a distribution dominated by linear species, consistent with the kinetic disfavoring of branching noted throughout the literature. This explains the ~20-fold yield deficit of valine vs. glycine observed across all experimental systems (Johnson et al. 2008; Parker et al. 2011). Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and products at the pool margin during wet-dry cycling.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde (minor branched product)\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"awaruite (Ni3Fe)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"420-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high (100-500 bar)\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-Ni alloy/magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"High-temperature hydrothermal vent with rapid quenching. Isobutyraldehyde is a minor branched C4 product in the FTT product distribution; selectivity for branched aldehydes is low (~1-3% of C4 fraction).\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"FTT synthesis builds carbon chains via surface carbide/methylene insertion. Branching occurs when a surface methyl group inserts at a secondary carbon position rather than at the chain terminus. The resulting branched C4 oxygenate (isobutyraldehyde) is released from the catalyst surface. Branching probability is controlled by surface coverage and temperature \u2014 higher temperatures and Fe-Ni bimetallic surfaces slightly favor branching over pure Fe catalysts.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"McCollom, Ritter & Simoneit (1999, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) showed FTT reactions produce distributions of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes including branched species. Anderson-Schulz-Flory product distributions from FTT include ~10-15% branched isomers in the C4 range. While isobutyraldehyde is not a major product, it provides a direct hydrothermal route to the valine Strecker precursor, bypassing the surface aldol diversification step. This is consistent with spark discharge experiments where radical recombination in reducing atmospheres generates branched aldehydes (Parker et al. 2011, PNAS).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Condensation of pyruvate and acetaldehyde to acetolactate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"iron oxyhydroxide (Fe(OH)2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"freshly precipitated Fe(OH)2 or FeS\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline conditions (pH 9-11) favor nucleophilic addition. Parallels biological acetolactate synthase but proceeds non-enzymatically on mineral surfaces.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of the acetaldehyde enolate (or enol) to the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of pyruvate, forming a C-C bond. Under alkaline conditions, acetaldehyde is partially deprotonated to its enolate form, which attacks the \u03b1-keto group of pyruvate. The resulting 2-acetolactate retains both the hydroxyl from the addition and the carboxylate from pyruvate. Fe(OH)2 surfaces coordinate the keto acid substrate and activate the aldehyde via Lewis acid catalysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This reaction parallels the biological acetolactate synthase step in valine biosynthesis. Copley, Smith & Morowitz (2005, PNAS) proposed that \u03b1-keto acid metabolism preceded amino acid synthesis and that condensation reactions of pyruvate with aldehydes would have been among the earliest C-C bond forming reactions. Muchowska, Varma & Moran (2019, Nature) demonstrated non-enzymatic Krebs cycle analogs on iron minerals. While this specific reaction (pyruvate + acetaldehyde \u2192 acetolactate) has not been independently verified for this exact substrate pair, the chemistry (aldol-type condensation of keto acids with aldehydes on Fe minerals) is well-precedented. This is flagged as partially speculative but represents the most metabolically congruent route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Decarboxylation of acetolactate to alpha-ketoisovalerate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface (Lewis acid sites facilitate decarboxylation)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Evaporitic pool, mild heating. Acetolactate undergoes spontaneous decarboxylation even without catalysis, but mineral surfaces accelerate the reaction. This is analogous to biological acetohydroxy acid isomeroreductase.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"\u03b2-Keto acid decarboxylation: the carboxylate group of acetolactate is lost as CO2, driven by the stability of the resulting enol which tautomerizes to the \u03b1-keto acid product. Montmorillonite Lewis acid sites coordinate the carboxylate, lowering the activation energy for C-C bond cleavage. The product \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid) retains the branched C4 skeleton with the \u03b1-keto group positioned for reductive amination to valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Decarboxylation of \u03b2-keto acids is thermodynamically facile and well-known in organic chemistry. Acetolactate decarboxylation is spontaneous at moderate temperatures (t\u00bd ~ hours at 50\u00b0C). Mineral surfaces including clays catalyze decarboxylation reactions through Lewis acid activation. This step generates \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, the direct reductive amination precursor to valine, paralleling the biological pathway (Copley, Smith & Morowitz, 2005, PNAS).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 1: imine formation and HCN addition to form valine aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (concentrates reactants, provides micro-alkaline surfaces)\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution at pH ~9 where free NH3 is available (pKa = 9.2). Evaporitic pool setting where concentration enhances reactant encounter rates. Oceanic HCN estimated at ~2\u00d710^-6 M at pH 8, 0\u00b0C (Miyakawa et al. 2002).\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-step one-pot reaction: (1) Isobutyraldehyde condenses with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH3)2CHCHO + NH3 \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH=NH + H2O. (2) HCN adds nucleophilically to the electrophilic imine carbon: (CH3)2CHCH=NH + HCN \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CN. The \u03b1-aminonitrile product is kinetically stable but thermodynamically metastable with respect to reversal. N-formylation in formamide solvent can protect the aminonitrile from reversion (Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021, 2023, JACS).\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Strecker synthesis is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids (Miller & Van Trump, 1981, Origin of Life). Keefe, Newton & Miller (1995, Nature) confirmed isobutyraldehyde as the specific Strecker precursor for valine. Devergne, Magrino, Pietrucci & Saitta (2021, J. Phys. Chem. Lett.) computed the full free-energy landscape confirming thermodynamic feasibility. Montmorillonite clay concentrates organic reactants through adsorption (Millman et al. 2024, GCA) and provides alkaline microenvironments favorable for Strecker chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Strecker synthesis step 2: hydrolysis of aminonitrile to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"310-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite surface catalyzes hydrolysis; mildly acidic to neutral pH accelerates nitrile hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool. Hydrolysis proceeds through an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-methylbutanamide). Half-life of aminonitrile hydrolysis <1000 years at 0\u00b0C, much faster at elevated temperatures (Miller, 1998). NH3 is regenerated as a byproduct.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-step irreversible hydrolysis: (1) Nucleophilic addition of H2O to the nitrile carbon: (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CN + H2O \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CONH2 (\u03b1-amino amide). (2) Second hydrolysis: (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CONH2 + H2O \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)COOH + NH3. The irreversibility of nitrile hydrolysis drives the overall Strecker equilibrium toward amino acid product. Product is racemic DL-valine.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Miller (1998) established aminonitrile hydrolysis half-lives, and all Miller-Urey analyses confirm Strecker hydrolysis as the amino acid-forming step. Johnson et al. (2008, Science) reanalyzed Miller's volcanic apparatus samples finding 22 amino acids including valine. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) found 23 amino acids in H2S-enriched experiments. Valine yields are ~0.04-0.05% of input carbon, approximately 5% the yield of glycine \u2014 consistent with the isobutyraldehyde availability bottleneck. Product is racemic DL-valine as observed in all abiotic synthesis experiments and meteorites (Kvenvolden et al. 1970, Nature; Pizzarello & Cronin, 2000, GCA).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs reaction: formation of 5-isopropylhydantoin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite clay\", \"phosphate minerals (struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"montmorillonite (concentrates reactants); struvite (NH4MgPO4\u00b76H2O) provides alkaline pH and ammonium\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Aqueous solution with dissolved CO2 or (NH4)2CO3. pH 8-9. Evaporitic pool setting. Hydantoin formation is thermodynamically more favorable than direct Strecker, providing a driving force for the reaction.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Multi-step cyclization: (1) Isobutyraldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). (2) Cyanohydrin reacts with NH3 to form aminonitrile. (3) In the presence of CO2 (or carbonate/carbamate), the amino group is carbamoylated, and intramolecular cyclization produces the 5-membered hydantoin ring (5-isopropylhydantoin). The cyclic hydantoin is thermodynamically more stable than the open-chain aminonitrile, driving the equilibrium forward.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated the Bucherer-Bergs variant as a prebiotic route bridging aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry with \u03b1-keto acid metabolism through hydantoin intermediates. The thermodynamic stability of the hydantoin ring provides a significant driving force absent in the direct Strecker pathway. Hydantoins are detected in meteorites (Pizzarello & Weber, 2010), confirming their prebiotic relevance.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of 5-isopropylhydantoin to valine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_001\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"none required; thermal hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Prebiotic pool with moderate heating. Hydrolysis proceeds through ring-opening of the hydantoin. CO2 and NH3 are released as byproducts. Slower than aminonitrile hydrolysis but irreversible.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise hydrolytic ring-opening: (1) First hydrolysis cleaves the C2-N3 bond of the hydantoin ring, producing N-carbamoyl-valine. (2) Second hydrolysis releases CO2 and NH3, yielding free racemic DL-valine. Both steps are irreversible under aqueous conditions, providing a strong thermodynamic driving force for complete conversion of the hydantoin to the free amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydantoin hydrolysis to amino acids is well-established in both chemistry and enzymology. Pulletikurti et al. (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated this as part of the Bucherer-Bergs prebiotic pathway. The two-step hydrolysis (hydantoin \u2192 N-carbamoyl amino acid \u2192 amino acid + CO2 + NH3) is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds at moderate temperatures without catalysis. This route avoids the reversibility issues of the direct Strecker aminonitrile intermediate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on FeS/H2S\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"moderate to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"freshly precipitated FeS; pyrite forms as coupled product\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Alkaline hydrothermal conditions (pH 9-11). FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e- provides reducing equivalents (\u0394G\u00b0 = -38.4 kJ/mol). The electrons drive the reductive amination. Mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III) oxyhydroxides optimize amino acid selectivity over hydroxy acid formation (Barge et al. 2019). Reaction yields racemic DL-valine.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Two-step reductive amination: (1) \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate condenses with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH3)2CHCOCOO- + NH3 \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(=NH)COO- + H2O. (2) The imine is reduced by electrons from pyrite-forming FeS/H2S coupling: (CH3)2CHCH(=NH)COO- + 2[H] \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)COO-. The overall reaction is driven by the exergonic pyrite formation reaction (FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + H2). The Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio controls selectivity for amino acid vs. hydroxy acid product.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user & Stetter (1995, Tetrahedron Lett.) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids using FeS/H2S. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Lett.) revisited this with freshly precipitated FeS and Fe(OH)2. Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) showed that mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide minerals achieve reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine at alkaline pH, with the Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio determining amino acid vs. hydroxy acid selectivity. Kaur, Rauscher, Werner et al. (2024, Chem) drove reductive amination of six biological keto acids using H2 on metallic Ni at 22\u00b0C and pH 8. The chemistry extends in principle to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, the valine precursor. This pathway is metabolically congruent with modern valine biosynthesis (transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Photocatalytic reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on pyrite\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"TiO2 (anatase)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"natural pyrite surface under UV/visible light; TiO2 as co-photocatalyst\",\n        \"aqueous\": true,\n        \"other\": \"Surface pool exposed to solar UV radiation (no ozone layer on early Earth). Pyrite bandgap (~0.95 eV) enables visible-light absorption. H2O serves as the terminal electron donor via photo-oxidation on the pyrite surface: 2H2O \u2192 O2 + 4H+ + 4e- (or more likely, water acts as sacrificial donor producing H2O2 under anoxic conditions). Reaction produces D-enantiomeric excess of 14.5-42.4% due to wavy atomic arrangement of pyrite surface.\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photocatalytic process: (1) UV/visible light excites electrons in pyrite from valence to conduction band. (2) Photo-generated electrons reduce the imine intermediate formed from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH3 condensation. (3) Photo-generated holes oxidize water (H2O \u2192 OH\u2022 + H+ + e-) providing the protons for the reduction. Net reaction: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH3 + H2O + h\u03bd \u2192 valine + \u00bdO2 (or H2O2 under anoxic conditions). The chiral pyrite surface induces enantioselective synthesis through its intrinsic wavy atomic arrangement.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"A 2024 study in Nature Communications revealed that natural pyrite surfaces exhibit photocatalytic reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids under light, with D-enantiomeric excesses of 14.5-42.4% driven by the wavy atomic arrangement of the pyrite surface. Wang et al. (2012, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) showed ZnS-catalyzed reversible amination of \u03b1-oxo acids on photo-illuminated surfaces. TiO2 photocatalysis drives C-C bond formation with negligible temperature dependence (Saladino et al. 2006, PNAS). Water serves as the explicit electron donor in the photocatalytic cycle, addressing the stoichiometric requirement for reducing equivalents. This is the only known pathway producing enantiomerically enriched amino acids from simple precursors.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol diversification \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis generates acetaldehyde at hydrothermal vents, which is transported to surface evaporitic pools where NiS-catalyzed aldol diversification produces isobutyraldehyde as a minor branched product. Strecker synthesis with NH3 and HCN on montmorillonite surfaces yields valine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to racemic valine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"NiS-acetylene \u2192 aldol diversification \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetylene hydration on NiS surfaces at hydrothermal vents produces acetaldehyde, which feeds into surface aldol diversification and Strecker chemistry. Shorter hydrothermal step leveraging Preiner et al. (2023) NiS catalysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"CO2 is fixed to pyruvate on greigite at hydrothermal vents. Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, which then feeds into the surface aldol-Strecker pathway. This is the longest pathway but most metabolically congruent, connecting carbon fixation to amino acid synthesis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct FTT isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis directly produces isobutyraldehyde as a minor branched C4 product, bypassing the aldol diversification step. Shorter but lower-yield pathway reflecting Anderson-Schulz-Flory branching statistics.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 hydantoin \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Same acetaldehyde-to-isobutyraldehyde generation as P1, but the amino acid is formed via the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway rather than direct Strecker. The hydantoin intermediate provides greater thermodynamic driving force and protection against aminonitrile reversion.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"NiS-acetylene \u2192 aldol \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 hydantoin \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetylene-derived acetaldehyde feeds into the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route. Combines Preiner et al. NiS catalysis with Pulletikurti et al. hydantoin chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Full carbon fixation pathway through pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, aldol diversification, and Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route. Longest pathway with maximum metabolic congruence and thermodynamic driving force from hydantoin stability.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct FTT isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Shortest Bucherer-Bergs pathway: FTT-derived isobutyraldehyde directly enters hydantoin formation. Minimal steps but limited by low FTT branched aldehyde yields.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 \u2192 pyruvate + FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 FeS reductive amination \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Metabolically congruent pathway paralleling biological valine biosynthesis: pyruvate condenses with acetaldehyde (from FTT) to form acetolactate on Fe(OH)2/FeS surfaces. Decarboxylation yields \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, which undergoes reductive amination coupled to pyrite formation on FeS/H2S. Entirely hydrothermal/surface chemistry.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"CO2 \u2192 pyruvate + NiS-acetaldehyde \u2192 acetolactate \u2192 \u03b1-ketoisovalerate \u2192 pyrite photocatalytic amination \u2192 valine\",\n      \"description\": \"Combined metabolic and photocatalytic pathway: pyruvate (from CO2 fixation) condenses with NiS-derived acetaldehyde to form acetolactate. Decarboxylation produces \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, which is reductively aminated on pyrite surfaces under UV light using water as electron donor. This is the only pathway producing enantiomerically enriched valine (D-excess 14.5-42.4%).\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_014\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_012\", \"mol_014\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"description\": \"Acetaldehyde is the primary C2 building block hub, formed through three independent hydrothermal routes and consumed in two distinct downstream pathways. Its abundance relative to branched aldehydes is the key factor controlling the glycine/valine yield ratio.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate is the central C3 \u03b1-keto acid hub, connecting CO2 fixation to both acetaldehyde generation (via decarboxylation) and the metabolically congruent acetolactate condensation pathway. It bridges hydrothermal carbon fixation with downstream amino acid synthesis.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"description\": \"Isobutyraldehyde is the critical branched C4 aldehyde whose availability constitutes the central bottleneck in prebiotic valine synthesis. Formed by two routes (NiS aldol diversification and direct FTT), it feeds both the Strecker and Bucherer-Bergs pathways. Its low yield (~1-5% of aldol products) explains the ~20-fold deficit of valine vs. glycine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"description\": \"\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is the metabolically congruent entry point to valine, formed via the acetolactate decarboxylation pathway. It feeds two independent reductive amination routes: FeS/H2S-coupled (hydrothermal) and pyrite photocatalytic (surface), the latter producing the only known enantiomerically enriched valine.\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"description\": \"Valine (target molecule) is the convergence endpoint of all 10 pathways, formed through four distinct final reactions: Strecker hydrolysis (rxn_011), Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin hydrolysis (rxn_013), FeS reductive amination (rxn_014), and pyrite photocatalytic amination (rxn_015).\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Valine (2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid)", "overall_strategy": "The network models valine synthesis through three major convergent strategies grounded in the literature: (1) Strecker synthesis from isobutyraldehyde, HCN, and NH3 \u2014 the most experimentally validated route (Miller & Van Trump 1981; Keefe, Newton & Miller 1995); (2) Bucherer-Bergs variant through a hydantoin intermediate when CO2 is present (Pulletikurti et al. 2022); and (3) reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate on iron-sulfur minerals, paralleling biological biosynthesis (Hafenbradl et al. 1995; Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 2003; 2024 Nature Communications pyrite photocatalysis). The central bottleneck \u2014 prebiotic generation of the branched C4 aldehyde isobutyraldehyde \u2014 is addressed via two routes: NiS-catalyzed aldol diversification of acetaldehyde (Preiner et al. 2023) producing branched species among a complex mixture, and direct Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis as a minor branched product on Fe-Ni catalysts (McCollom et al. 1999). Acetaldehyde itself is generated through three independent hydrothermal pathways (FTT, NiS-acetylene hydration, pyruvate decarboxylation), creating robust network redundancy. The metabolically congruent \u03b1-ketoisovalerate route proceeds via pyruvate-acetaldehyde condensation to acetolactate followed by decarboxylation, paralleling biological acetolactate synthase logic (Copley, Smith & Morowitz 2005). Four hub molecules (acetaldehyde, pyruvate, isobutyraldehyde, \u03b1-ketoisovalerate) create the convergence topology. The ~20-fold yield deficit of valine vs. glycine observed across all experimental systems (Johnson et al. 2008; Parker et al. 2011; meteoritic data) is an intrinsic consequence of the kinetic and thermodynamic cost of C4 branching in aldol chemistry.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen gas", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "CO", "iupac_name": "carbon monoxide", "common_name": "carbon monoxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO/c1-2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "H2O", "iupac_name": "water", "common_name": "water", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2O/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "ammonia", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "H2S", "iupac_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "common_name": "hydrogen sulfide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2S/h1H2", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H2", "iupac_name": "ethyne", "common_name": "acetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2/c1-2/h1-2H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "CHO2-", "iupac_name": "formate", "common_name": "formate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O2/c2-1-3/h1H,(H,2,3)/p-1", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C2H4O", "iupac_name": "acetaldehyde", "common_name": "acetaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O/c1-2-3/h2H,1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvate / pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H8O", "iupac_name": "2-methylpropanal", "common_name": "isobutyraldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H8O/c1-3(2)4-5/h3-4H,1-2H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C5H10N2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanenitrile", "common_name": "valine aminonitrile", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H10N2/c1-3(2)4(6)5-7/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H8O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O3/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C6H10N2O2", "iupac_name": "5-(propan-2-yl)-imidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5-isopropylhydantoin", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H10N2O2/c1-3(2)4-5(9)8-6(10)7-4/h3-4H,1-2H3,(H2,7,8,9,10)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C5H8O4", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-methyl-3-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "acetolactate (2-acetolactic acid)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H8O4/c1-3(6)4(2,9)5(7)8/h9H,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C5H11NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-3-methylbutanoic acid", "common_name": "valine (DL-valine)", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H11NO2/c1-3(2)4(6)5(7)8/h3-4H,6H2,1-2H3,(H,7,8)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "CO2 hydrogenation to formate on greigite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, H2-rich serpentinization fluids"}, "mechanism": "CO2 binds to Fe-S cluster surface of greigite (structural analog of biological [Fe4S4] clusters). H2 dissociates on mineral surface providing reducing equivalents. Two-electron reduction of CO2 to formate (HCOO-) proceeds via a surface-bound formate intermediate. This is the first step in the reductive acetyl-CoA pathway analog.", "reasoning": "Greigite-catalyzed CO2 reduction to formate is thermodynamically favorable under alkaline hydrothermal conditions (Amend & Shock, 1998, Science). Russell et al. (1994) proposed greigite as a structural and functional analog of biological ferredoxin [Fe4S4] clusters. Martin & Russell (2007, Philos. Trans. R. Soc. B) elaborated this as the basis of a primitive acetyl-CoA pathway. Formate serves as a C1 building block for downstream synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "awaruite (Ni3Fe)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high (100-500 bar)", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4) and Fe-Ni alloy", "aqueous": true, "other": "Black smoker/high-temperature vent with rapid quenching to preserve products"}, "mechanism": "CO adsorbs on Fe-Ni catalyst surface, dissociates to surface carbide and oxide. Sequential hydrogenation builds C1 to C2 chain (surface CH2 + CHO coupling). Acetaldehyde (CH3CHO) is released as a C2 oxygenated product alongside methanol, ethanol, and higher homologs. Product preservation requires rapid cooling as amino acids degrade above 240\u00b0C (Miller & Bada, 1988).", "reasoning": "McCollom, Ritter & Simoneit (1999, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) demonstrated FTT synthesis of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes from CO + H2 on Fe catalysts at 150-300\u00b0C. Acetaldehyde is a common C2 oxygenated product. Rapid quenching upon mixing with cold seawater preserves products (Chandru et al., 2013, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.). This is the primary hydrothermal route to the C2 aldehyde required for aldol chain extension."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "NiS-catalyzed acetylene hydration to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["nickel sulfide (NiS)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate (10-100 bar)", "catalyst": "freshly precipitated NiS", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal conditions, pH 8-10"}, "mechanism": "Acetylene coordinates to Ni(II) centers on the NiS surface. Nucleophilic addition of water across the triple bond, facilitated by the metal center, produces vinyl alcohol which tautomerizes to acetaldehyde (Markovnikov addition). NiS acts as a heterogeneous catalyst recycled on the mineral surface.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2023, Nature Communications) demonstrated that NiS catalyzes acetylene chemistry to produce acetaldehyde, which then undergoes aldol diversification to higher aldehydes including branched species. This provides a direct hydrothermal route to the C2 building block. Acetylene is produced by high-temperature volcanic chemistry and serpentinization processes."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "CO2 reduction to pyruvate on greigite/magnetite", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high (50-200 bar)", "catalyst": "greigite/magnetite mixed phases", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal vent, pH 9-11, strongly reducing (H2-rich)"}, "mechanism": "Multi-step CO2 fixation on Fe-S mineral surfaces. CO2 is first reduced to formate, then to formaldehyde/CO equivalents, which undergo C-C coupling on the mineral surface to build the C3 backbone. The \u03b1-keto acid functional group arises from partial oxidation during the assembly. Pyruvate is thermodynamically the most stable C3 keto acid under these conditions.", "reasoning": "Muchowska, Varma & Moran (2019, Nature) demonstrated non-enzymatic Krebs cycle analogs including pyruvate formation from simple precursors on iron-containing minerals. Amend & Shock (1998, Science) calculated that autotrophic synthesis of organic molecules including amino acid precursors is exergonic under hot, moderately reduced hydrothermal conditions. Pyruvate is a central metabolic hub in both modern and plausibly prebiotic metabolism."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate to acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_001"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "pyrite surface (facilitates decarboxylation)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Thermal decarboxylation favored at higher temperatures in hydrothermal fluids"}, "mechanism": "Non-oxidative decarboxylation of pyruvate: CH3COCOO- \u2192 CH3CHO + CO2. The \u03b2-keto acid undergoes facile loss of CO2 from the carboxylate group. Mineral surfaces (pyrite, magnetite) lower the activation energy by stabilizing the transition state through surface coordination of the carboxylate. This is the reverse of the carboxylation that forms pyruvate.", "reasoning": "Thermal decarboxylation of pyruvate is a well-established reaction; pyruvate decarboxylation occurs readily at temperatures above 70\u00b0C and is accelerated by mineral surfaces. This provides a third independent route to acetaldehyde. The reaction parallels biological pyruvate decarboxylase activity and connects the C3 keto acid pool to the C2 aldehyde pool essential for valine precursor synthesis."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "NiS-catalyzed aldol diversification of acetaldehyde to branched aldehydes", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["nickel sulfide (NiS)", "montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "NiS particles on montmorillonite", "aqueous": true, "other": "Mildly alkaline evaporitic pool (pH 8-10). Reaction produces a complex mixture of linear and branched C3-C6 aldehydes; isobutyraldehyde is a minor but thermodynamically accessible branched C4 product. Yield of isobutyraldehyde estimated at ~1-5% of total aldol products."}, "mechanism": "Acetaldehyde undergoes repeated aldol condensation and retro-aldol scrambling on NiS surfaces. The initial aldol of two acetaldehydes yields 3-hydroxybutanal (acetaldol, linear C4), which can dehydrate to crotonaldehyde or undergo retro-aldol to regenerate C2 fragments. Under continued cycling, cross-aldol reactions and retro-aldol/re-aldol scrambling produce a statistical distribution of C3-C6 aldehydes including both linear (butanal, pentanal) and branched species (isobutyraldehyde, 2-methylbutanal). The branched isobutyraldehyde is formed when a C1 formyl fragment from retro-aldol adds to propionaldehyde, or through methylation-equivalent rearrangements on the NiS surface. NiS catalysis lowers activation barriers for both forward aldol and retro-aldol, enabling thermodynamic equilibration that populates branched isomers.", "reasoning": "Preiner et al. (2023, Nature Communications) demonstrated NiS-catalyzed acetaldehyde diversification to higher aldehydes including branched species. This is NOT a simple stoichiometric aldol of 2 acetaldehydes to isobutyraldehyde; rather, it is a complex catalytic scrambling process. The branched C4 aldehyde (isobutyraldehyde) is a minor product (~1-5%) in a distribution dominated by linear species, consistent with the kinetic disfavoring of branching noted throughout the literature. This explains the ~20-fold yield deficit of valine vs. glycine observed across all experimental systems (Johnson et al. 2008; Parker et al. 2011). Montmorillonite concentrates reactants and products at the pool margin during wet-dry cycling."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis of isobutyraldehyde (minor branched product)", "inputs": ["mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "awaruite (Ni3Fe)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "420-500K", "pressure": "high (100-500 bar)", "catalyst": "Fe-Ni alloy/magnetite", "aqueous": true, "other": "High-temperature hydrothermal vent with rapid quenching. Isobutyraldehyde is a minor branched C4 product in the FTT product distribution; selectivity for branched aldehydes is low (~1-3% of C4 fraction)."}, "mechanism": "FTT synthesis builds carbon chains via surface carbide/methylene insertion. Branching occurs when a surface methyl group inserts at a secondary carbon position rather than at the chain terminus. The resulting branched C4 oxygenate (isobutyraldehyde) is released from the catalyst surface. Branching probability is controlled by surface coverage and temperature \u2014 higher temperatures and Fe-Ni bimetallic surfaces slightly favor branching over pure Fe catalysts.", "reasoning": "McCollom, Ritter & Simoneit (1999, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) showed FTT reactions produce distributions of hydrocarbons, alcohols, and aldehydes including branched species. Anderson-Schulz-Flory product distributions from FTT include ~10-15% branched isomers in the C4 range. While isobutyraldehyde is not a major product, it provides a direct hydrothermal route to the valine Strecker precursor, bypassing the surface aldol diversification step. This is consistent with spark discharge experiments where radical recombination in reducing atmospheres generates branched aldehydes (Parker et al. 2011, PNAS)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Condensation of pyruvate and acetaldehyde to acetolactate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "iron oxyhydroxide (Fe(OH)2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "freshly precipitated Fe(OH)2 or FeS", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline conditions (pH 9-11) favor nucleophilic addition. Parallels biological acetolactate synthase but proceeds non-enzymatically on mineral surfaces."}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of the acetaldehyde enolate (or enol) to the electrophilic carbonyl carbon of pyruvate, forming a C-C bond. Under alkaline conditions, acetaldehyde is partially deprotonated to its enolate form, which attacks the \u03b1-keto group of pyruvate. The resulting 2-acetolactate retains both the hydroxyl from the addition and the carboxylate from pyruvate. Fe(OH)2 surfaces coordinate the keto acid substrate and activate the aldehyde via Lewis acid catalysis.", "reasoning": "This reaction parallels the biological acetolactate synthase step in valine biosynthesis. Copley, Smith & Morowitz (2005, PNAS) proposed that \u03b1-keto acid metabolism preceded amino acid synthesis and that condensation reactions of pyruvate with aldehydes would have been among the earliest C-C bond forming reactions. Muchowska, Varma & Moran (2019, Nature) demonstrated non-enzymatic Krebs cycle analogs on iron minerals. While this specific reaction (pyruvate + acetaldehyde \u2192 acetolactate) has not been independently verified for this exact substrate pair, the chemistry (aldol-type condensation of keto acids with aldehydes on Fe minerals) is well-precedented. This is flagged as partially speculative but represents the most metabolically congruent route to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Decarboxylation of acetolactate to alpha-ketoisovalerate", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_001"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (apatite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface (Lewis acid sites facilitate decarboxylation)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Evaporitic pool, mild heating. Acetolactate undergoes spontaneous decarboxylation even without catalysis, but mineral surfaces accelerate the reaction. This is analogous to biological acetohydroxy acid isomeroreductase."}, "mechanism": "\u03b2-Keto acid decarboxylation: the carboxylate group of acetolactate is lost as CO2, driven by the stability of the resulting enol which tautomerizes to the \u03b1-keto acid product. Montmorillonite Lewis acid sites coordinate the carboxylate, lowering the activation energy for C-C bond cleavage. The product \u03b1-ketoisovalerate (3-methyl-2-oxobutanoic acid) retains the branched C4 skeleton with the \u03b1-keto group positioned for reductive amination to valine.", "reasoning": "Decarboxylation of \u03b2-keto acids is thermodynamically facile and well-known in organic chemistry. Acetolactate decarboxylation is spontaneous at moderate temperatures (t\u00bd ~ hours at 50\u00b0C). Mineral surfaces including clays catalyze decarboxylation reactions through Lewis acid activation. This step generates \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, the direct reductive amination precursor to valine, paralleling the biological pathway (Copley, Smith & Morowitz, 2005, PNAS)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 1: imine formation and HCN addition to form valine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_005", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (concentrates reactants, provides micro-alkaline surfaces)", "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous solution at pH ~9 where free NH3 is available (pKa = 9.2). Evaporitic pool setting where concentration enhances reactant encounter rates. Oceanic HCN estimated at ~2\u00d710^-6 M at pH 8, 0\u00b0C (Miyakawa et al. 2002)."}, "mechanism": "Two-step one-pot reaction: (1) Isobutyraldehyde condenses with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH3)2CHCHO + NH3 \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH=NH + H2O. (2) HCN adds nucleophilically to the electrophilic imine carbon: (CH3)2CHCH=NH + HCN \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CN. The \u03b1-aminonitrile product is kinetically stable but thermodynamically metastable with respect to reversal. N-formylation in formamide solvent can protect the aminonitrile from reversion (Green, Xu & Sutherland, 2021, 2023, JACS).", "reasoning": "The Strecker synthesis is the most experimentally validated prebiotic route to \u03b1-amino acids (Miller & Van Trump, 1981, Origin of Life). Keefe, Newton & Miller (1995, Nature) confirmed isobutyraldehyde as the specific Strecker precursor for valine. Devergne, Magrino, Pietrucci & Saitta (2021, J. Phys. Chem. Lett.) computed the full free-energy landscape confirming thermodynamic feasibility. Montmorillonite clay concentrates organic reactants through adsorption (Millman et al. 2024, GCA) and provides alkaline microenvironments favorable for Strecker chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Strecker synthesis step 2: hydrolysis of aminonitrile to valine", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_005"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay"], "conditions": {"temperature": "310-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite surface catalyzes hydrolysis; mildly acidic to neutral pH accelerates nitrile hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "Wet-dry cycling in evaporitic pool. Hydrolysis proceeds through an amide intermediate (2-amino-3-methylbutanamide). Half-life of aminonitrile hydrolysis <1000 years at 0\u00b0C, much faster at elevated temperatures (Miller, 1998). NH3 is regenerated as a byproduct."}, "mechanism": "Two-step irreversible hydrolysis: (1) Nucleophilic addition of H2O to the nitrile carbon: (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CN + H2O \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CONH2 (\u03b1-amino amide). (2) Second hydrolysis: (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)CONH2 + H2O \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)COOH + NH3. The irreversibility of nitrile hydrolysis drives the overall Strecker equilibrium toward amino acid product. Product is racemic DL-valine.", "reasoning": "Miller (1998) established aminonitrile hydrolysis half-lives, and all Miller-Urey analyses confirm Strecker hydrolysis as the amino acid-forming step. Johnson et al. (2008, Science) reanalyzed Miller's volcanic apparatus samples finding 22 amino acids including valine. Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) found 23 amino acids in H2S-enriched experiments. Valine yields are ~0.04-0.05% of input carbon, approximately 5% the yield of glycine \u2014 consistent with the isobutyraldehyde availability bottleneck. Product is racemic DL-valine as observed in all abiotic synthesis experiments and meteorites (Kvenvolden et al. 1970, Nature; Pizzarello & Cronin, 2000, GCA)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs reaction: formation of 5-isopropylhydantoin", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_006", "mol_005", "mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite clay", "phosphate minerals (struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (concentrates reactants); struvite (NH4MgPO4\u00b76H2O) provides alkaline pH and ammonium", "aqueous": true, "other": "Aqueous solution with dissolved CO2 or (NH4)2CO3. pH 8-9. Evaporitic pool setting. Hydantoin formation is thermodynamically more favorable than direct Strecker, providing a driving force for the reaction."}, "mechanism": "Multi-step cyclization: (1) Isobutyraldehyde + HCN \u2192 cyanohydrin (2-hydroxy-3-methylbutanenitrile). (2) Cyanohydrin reacts with NH3 to form aminonitrile. (3) In the presence of CO2 (or carbonate/carbamate), the amino group is carbamoylated, and intramolecular cyclization produces the 5-membered hydantoin ring (5-isopropylhydantoin). The cyclic hydantoin is thermodynamically more stable than the open-chain aminonitrile, driving the equilibrium forward.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated the Bucherer-Bergs variant as a prebiotic route bridging aldehyde-based Strecker chemistry with \u03b1-keto acid metabolism through hydantoin intermediates. The thermodynamic stability of the hydantoin ring provides a significant driving force absent in the direct Strecker pathway. Hydantoins are detected in meteorites (Pizzarello & Weber, 2010), confirming their prebiotic relevance."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrolysis of 5-isopropylhydantoin to valine", "inputs": ["mol_015", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_001", "mol_005"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "none required; thermal hydrolysis", "aqueous": true, "other": "Prebiotic pool with moderate heating. Hydrolysis proceeds through ring-opening of the hydantoin. CO2 and NH3 are released as byproducts. Slower than aminonitrile hydrolysis but irreversible."}, "mechanism": "Stepwise hydrolytic ring-opening: (1) First hydrolysis cleaves the C2-N3 bond of the hydantoin ring, producing N-carbamoyl-valine. (2) Second hydrolysis releases CO2 and NH3, yielding free racemic DL-valine. Both steps are irreversible under aqueous conditions, providing a strong thermodynamic driving force for complete conversion of the hydantoin to the free amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydantoin hydrolysis to amino acids is well-established in both chemistry and enzymology. Pulletikurti et al. (2022, Nature Chemistry) demonstrated this as part of the Bucherer-Bergs prebiotic pathway. The two-step hydrolysis (hydantoin \u2192 N-carbamoyl amino acid \u2192 amino acid + CO2 + NH3) is thermodynamically favorable and proceeds at moderate temperatures without catalysis. This route avoids the reversibility issues of the direct Strecker aminonitrile intermediate."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on FeS/H2S", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_017", "mol_004"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "moderate to high", "catalyst": "freshly precipitated FeS; pyrite forms as coupled product", "aqueous": true, "other": "Alkaline hydrothermal conditions (pH 9-11). FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + 2H+ + 2e- provides reducing equivalents (\u0394G\u00b0 = -38.4 kJ/mol). The electrons drive the reductive amination. Mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III) oxyhydroxides optimize amino acid selectivity over hydroxy acid formation (Barge et al. 2019). Reaction yields racemic DL-valine."}, "mechanism": "Two-step reductive amination: (1) \u03b1-Ketoisovalerate condenses with NH3 to form an imine (Schiff base): (CH3)2CHCOCOO- + NH3 \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(=NH)COO- + H2O. (2) The imine is reduced by electrons from pyrite-forming FeS/H2S coupling: (CH3)2CHCH(=NH)COO- + 2[H] \u2192 (CH3)2CHCH(NH2)COO-. The overall reaction is driven by the exergonic pyrite formation reaction (FeS + H2S \u2192 FeS2 + H2). The Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio controls selectivity for amino acid vs. hydroxy acid product.", "reasoning": "Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user & Stetter (1995, Tetrahedron Lett.) demonstrated reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids using FeS/H2S. Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, Tetrahedron Lett.) revisited this with freshly precipitated FeS and Fe(OH)2. Barge et al. (2019, PNAS) showed that mixed-valence iron oxyhydroxide minerals achieve reductive amination of pyruvate to alanine at alkaline pH, with the Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio determining amino acid vs. hydroxy acid selectivity. Kaur, Rauscher, Werner et al. (2024, Chem) drove reductive amination of six biological keto acids using H2 on metallic Ni at 22\u00b0C and pH 8. The chemistry extends in principle to \u03b1-ketoisovalerate, the valine precursor. This pathway is metabolically congruent with modern valine biosynthesis (transamination of \u03b1-ketoisovalerate)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Photocatalytic reductive amination of alpha-ketoisovalerate on pyrite", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_005", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "TiO2 (anatase)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "natural pyrite surface under UV/visible light; TiO2 as co-photocatalyst", "aqueous": true, "other": "Surface pool exposed to solar UV radiation (no ozone layer on early Earth). Pyrite bandgap (~0.95 eV) enables visible-light absorption. H2O serves as the terminal electron donor via photo-oxidation on the pyrite surface: 2H2O \u2192 O2 + 4H+ + 4e- (or more likely, water acts as sacrificial donor producing H2O2 under anoxic conditions). Reaction produces D-enantiomeric excess of 14.5-42.4% due to wavy atomic arrangement of pyrite surface."}, "mechanism": "Photocatalytic process: (1) UV/visible light excites electrons in pyrite from valence to conduction band. (2) Photo-generated electrons reduce the imine intermediate formed from \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH3 condensation. (3) Photo-generated holes oxidize water (H2O \u2192 OH\u2022 + H+ + e-) providing the protons for the reduction. Net reaction: \u03b1-ketoisovalerate + NH3 + H2O + h\u03bd \u2192 valine + \u00bdO2 (or H2O2 under anoxic conditions). The chiral pyrite surface induces enantioselective synthesis through its intrinsic wavy atomic arrangement.", "reasoning": "A 2024 study in Nature Communications revealed that natural pyrite surfaces exhibit photocatalytic reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids to amino acids under light, with D-enantiomeric excesses of 14.5-42.4% driven by the wavy atomic arrangement of the pyrite surface. Wang et al. (2012, Origins Life Evol. Biosph.) showed ZnS-catalyzed reversible amination of \u03b1-oxo acids on photo-illuminated surfaces. TiO2 photocatalysis drives C-C bond formation with negligible temperature dependence (Saladino et al. 2006, PNAS). Water serves as the explicit electron donor in the photocatalytic cycle, addressing the stoichiometric requirement for reducing equivalents. This is the only known pathway producing enantiomerically enriched amino acids from simple precursors."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol diversification \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine", "description": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis generates acetaldehyde at hydrothermal vents, which is transported to surface evaporitic pools where NiS-catalyzed aldol diversification produces isobutyraldehyde as a minor branched product. Strecker synthesis with NH3 and HCN on montmorillonite surfaces yields valine aminonitrile, which hydrolyzes to racemic valine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "NiS-acetylene \u2192 aldol diversification \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine", "description": "Acetylene hydration on NiS surfaces at hydrothermal vents produces acetaldehyde, which feeds into surface aldol diversification and Strecker chemistry. Shorter hydrothermal step leveraging Preiner et al. (2023) NiS catalysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "CO2 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine", "description": "CO2 is fixed to pyruvate on greigite at hydrothermal vents. Pyruvate undergoes thermal decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, which then feeds into the surface aldol-Strecker pathway. This is the longest pathway but most metabolically congruent, connecting carbon fixation to amino acid synthesis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Direct FTT isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Strecker \u2192 valine", "description": "Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis directly produces isobutyraldehyde as a minor branched C4 product, bypassing the aldol diversification step. Shorter but lower-yield pathway reflecting Anderson-Schulz-Flory branching statistics.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_010", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "FTT acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 hydantoin \u2192 valine", "description": "Same acetaldehyde-to-isobutyraldehyde generation as P1, but the amino acid is formed via the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin pathway rather than direct Strecker. The hydantoin intermediate provides greater thermodynamic driving force and protection against aminonitrile reversion.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "NiS-acetylene \u2192 aldol \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 hydantoin \u2192 valine", "description": "Acetylene-derived acetaldehyde feeds into the Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route. Combines Preiner et al. NiS catalysis with Pulletikurti et al. hydantoin chemistry.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_003", "rxn_006", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "CO2 \u2192 pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde \u2192 aldol \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 valine", "description": "Full carbon fixation pathway through pyruvate decarboxylation to acetaldehyde, aldol diversification, and Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route. Longest pathway with maximum metabolic congruence and thermodynamic driving force from hydantoin stability.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_010", "mol_012", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Direct FTT isobutyraldehyde \u2192 Bucherer-Bergs \u2192 valine", "description": "Shortest Bucherer-Bergs pathway: FTT-derived isobutyraldehyde directly enters hydantoin formation. Minimal steps but limited by low FTT branched aldehyde yields.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_012", "mol_0