oth acetaldehyde generation (via decarboxylation) and the metabolically congruent acetolactate condensation pathway. It bridges hydrothermal carbon fixation with downstream amino acid synthesis.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_012", "description": "Isobutyraldehyde is the critical branched C4 aldehyde whose availability constitutes the central bottleneck in prebiotic valine synthesis. Formed by two routes (NiS aldol diversification and direct FTT), it feeds both the Strecker and Bucherer-Bergs pathways. Its low yield (~1-5% of aldol products) explains the ~20-fold deficit of valine vs. glycine.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_012"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_014", "description": "\u03b1-Ketoisovalerate is the metabolically congruent entry point to valine, formed via the acetolactate decarboxylation pathway. It feeds two independent reductive amination routes: FeS/H2S-coupled (hydrothermal) and pyrite photocatalytic (surface), the latter producing the only known enantiomerically enriched valine.", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_009"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014", "rxn_015"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_017", "description": "Valine (target molecule) is the convergence endpoint of all 10 pathways, formed through four distinct final reactions: Strecker hydrolysis (rxn_011), Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin hydrolysis (rxn_013), FeS reductive amination (rxn_014), and pyrite photocatalytic amination (rxn_015).", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_011", "rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_015"], "outgoing_reactions": []}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 472617.18797683716, "success": true, "error_message": null}
